  functions:
  - '<br>Metabolism: The liver plays a central role in the metabolism of carbohydrates,
    proteins, and fats. It converts glucose into glycogen, which can be stored in
    the liver and used as an energy source when needed.<br> <br>Detoxification: The
    liver plays a crucial role in detoxifying the body by breaking down and removing
    toxins, drugs, and metabolic waste products from the bloodstream.<br><br>Synthesis:
    The liver synthesizes many essential proteins, including blood-clotting factors
    and albumin, which helps to maintain blood pressure and transport molecules throughout
    the body. <br><br>Storage: The liver stores vitamins, minerals, and other essential
    nutrients, such as iron and copper.'
  - '<br>Protection: The pleura helps protect the lungs by creating a fluid-filled
    sac around them. This sac acts as a cushion, reducing friction and preventing
    the lungs from rubbing against the chest wall.<br><br>Lubrication: The pleural
    fluid that fills the pleural cavity acts as a lubricant, allowing the lungs to
    move smoothly as we breathe.<br><br>Breathing: The pleura is essential for breathing.
    When we inhale, the diaphragm contracts, and the chest cavity expands, causing
    the lungs to expand as well. The pleura keeps the lungs attached to the chest
    wall, allowing them to move as the chest expands.<br><br>Immune defense: The
    pleura contains lymphatic vessels that help remove waste products and protect
    against infection.'
  - '<br>Storage: The stomach can expand and contract to accommodate food as it is
    ingested. This allows it to store food until it is ready to be digested.<br><br>Mixing
    and churning: The stomach uses its muscles to mix and churn food with digestive
    juices such as hydrochloric acid and enzymes. This process breaks down food into
    smaller particles and prepares it for further digestion in the small intestine.
    <br><br>Secretion: The stomach secretes a number of substances that aid in digestion,
    including hydrochloric acid, pepsin, and mucus. Hydrochloric acid helps to break
    down proteins, while pepsin is an enzyme that digests proteins. Mucus helps to
    protect the stomach lining from the acidic environment.<br><br>Absorption: The
    stomach is not a major site of nutrient absorption, but some nutrients, such
    as alcohol and certain medications, can be absorbed through the stomach lining.'
